                                            </h3><p class=3D"statisticsSlid=
er__desc responsiveText responsiveText--underlinedLinks"></p><p>Globally, a=
bout 25 percent of the population is under 15 years of age and 10 percent i=
s over 65 years of age. Africa has the youngest population worldwide. In Su=
b-Saharan Africa, more than 40 percent of the population is below 15 years,=
 and only three percent are above 65, indicating the <a href=3D"https://www=
.statista.com/statistics/1218173/life-expectancy-in-african-countries/" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" tabindex=3D"-1" aria-hidden=3D"true">low li=
fe expectancy</a> in several of the countries. In Europe, on the other hand=
, a higher share of the population is above 65 years than the population un=
der 15 years.</p>
Fertility rates
<p>The high share of children and youth in Africa is connected to the high =
fertility rates on the continent. For instance, South Sudan and Niger have =
the&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.statista.com/statistics/264687/countries-wi=
th-the-highest-population-growth-rate/" tabindex=3D"-1" aria-hidden=3D"true=
">highest population growth rates</a> globally. However, about 50 percent o=
f the world=E2=80=99s population live in countries with low fertility, wher=
e women have less than 2.1 children. Some countries in Europe, like Latvia =
and Lithuania, have experienced a&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.statista.com/=
statistics/264689/countries-with-the-highest-population-decline-rate/" tabi=
ndex=3D"-1" aria-hidden=3D"true">population decline </a>of one percent, and=
 in the Cook Islands, it is even above two percent. In Europe, the majority=
 of the population was previously working-aged adults with few dependents, =
but this trend is expected to reverse soon, and it is predicted that by 205=
0, the older population will outnumber the young in many developed countrie=
s.</p>
Growing global population
<p>As of 2025, there are 8.1 billion people living on the planet, and this =
is expected to reach more than nine billion before 2040. Moreover, the glob=
al population is <a href=3D"https://www.statista.com/statistics/262618/fore=
cast-about-the-development-of-the-world-population/" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener" tabindex=3D"-1" aria-hidden=3D"true">expected to reach 10 bil=
lions</a> around 2060, before slowing and then even falling slightly by 210=
0. As the population growth rates indicate, a significant <a href=3D"https:=
//www.statista.com/statistics/272789/world-population-by-continent/" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" tabindex=3D"-1" aria-hidden=3D"true">share of =
